Ray generates them instantly: getray.app

28
00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:48.663
(DOOR CREAKING)

29
00:01:56.920 --> 00:01:58.904
(WHIMPERING)

30
00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:04.919
Kaylie!

31
00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:06.631
Shh!

32
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:25.799
(GUNSHOT)

33
00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:27.590
And I fired.

34
00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:31.708
As many times as I've had this dream...

35
00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.145
it's never been me before.

36
00:02:34.840 --> 00:02:36.346
Holding the gun.

37
00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:38.311
I know.

38
00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:41.745
That's very good.

39
00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:48.199
It implies a true. deeply-rooted acceptance of responsibility.

40
00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.639
And it tells me that you haven't only overcome your delusion

41
00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:52.159
in your conscious mind...

42
00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:54.679
but in his subconscious mind as well.

43
00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:57.439
It's my opinion that Tim is a healthy adult

44
00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:00.639
who represents no danger to himself or anyone else.

45
00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:04.399
And I believe he should be discharged. as the state requested.

46
00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:06.828
on his upcoming 21st birthday.

47
00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:10.823
(FOOTSTEPS)

48
00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:16.039
WOMAN: going once...

49
00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:18.359
eleven-five twice...

50
00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:19.919
- (GAVEL BANGS)
- Sold to the gentleman.

51
00:03:19.920 --> 00:03:21.967
Congratulations to you. sir.

52
00:03:21.993 --> 00:03:23.966
That's bidder number 131.

53
00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:28.719
All right. and our next item for bid

54
00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:33.479
is a gorgeous antique mirror. recovered from the Levesque Estate.

55
00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:36.399
The Lasser Glass is a well-traveled gem.

56
00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.959
It spent several seasons adorning the walls at Balmoral Castle.

57
00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:42.199
Scottish home of the Royal Family.

58
00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:45.599
This is the original glass and the original frame.

59
00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:49.079
The mirror is in remarkable condition. save for a small hairline fracture

60
00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:50.999
down in the lower right-hand corner.

61
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.879
The frame is carved out of one piece of Bavarian Black Cedar.

62
00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:56.639
And we will go ahead and start the bidding

63
00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:58.919
at a conservative ten thousand dollars.

64
00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:01.159
Do I have ten? Right here in front. Thank you. sir.

65
00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.039
DOCTOR: Your sister is picking you up. then?

66
00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:06.742
Her message even said something about helping me find a job.

67
00:04:07.400 --> 00:04:09.559
That'd be wonderful for your transition.

68
00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:11.399
AUCTIONEER: We're at 12.000 dollars on the phone...

69
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:13.599
You sure you don't want me to come with you?

70
00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:15.314
Some moral support?

71
00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:17.479
No. But thank you.

72
00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:20.039
I think I better do this part myself.

73
00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.839
- Wait up for us.
- Of course.

74
00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:25.679
Remember what we talked about.

75
00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:28.279
You've had a support system. a mandated support system.

76
00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:29.680
to help you get well.

77
00:04:29.706 --> 00:04:31.879
Kaylie had to get by on her own.

78
00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:35.599
It's very important that you reconnect with your sister.

79
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:39.700
But it's more important that you protect your recovery.

80
00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:43.246
Sixteen thousand.

81
00:04:43.272 --> 00:04:44.839
Sixteen thousand on Skype.

82
00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:47.232
That is sixteen. going once.

83
00:04:47.258 --> 00:04:48.599
Sixteen twice.

84
00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:50.879
Sold. Please pass along our congratulations.

85
00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:52.864
- See you tonight.
- OK.

86
00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.145
(DOOR BUZZES)

87
00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:04.184
(DOOR BUZZES)

88
00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:08.429
Son. just pull the door when it buzzes.

89
00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:10.830
(DOOR BUZZES)

90
00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:32.909
Hey. little brother.

91
00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:46.588
Your half of the estate.

92
00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:50.679
Oh. apartments.

93
00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:52.519
So all the studies say that you should transition

94
00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:54.319
to a place that isn't necessarily large.

95
00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:56.399
so I printed off some listings for studios.

96
00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.919
But in the meantime. until you find one you like.

97
00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:02.143
we would love it if you stayed with us.

98
00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:05.519
Kaylie. I don't know how to thank you.

99
00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:08.903
Well. I wanted to talk to you about all of this sooner.

100
00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:12.941
But suddenly they wouldn't let me in to see you.

101
00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.959
It wasn't...

102
00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:20.548
It wasn't that they wouldn't let you in to see me.

103
00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:26.300
I just had some things I needed to figure out for myself.

104
00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:32.465
I get it.

105
00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:35.559
I'm your family.

106
00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:38.431
The only thing that matters is that you're here now.

107
00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:48.305
(WHISPERING) I found it.

108
00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.999
- What do you mean?
- You know.

109
00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:58.759
It wasn't easy.

110
00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:00.599
I tracked it down mostly through second bidders.

111
00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:02.399
people who lost at the auctions.

112
00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:04.919
It was in storage. part of an estate collection in Bremen.

113
00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:07.599
It took me a year and a half to get it into our warehouse

114
00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.279
and it lasted less than a week.

115
00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:12.199
It's about to ship out to a new buyer. so we only have a few days.

116
00:07:12.200 --> 00:07:14.150
but it should be enough.

117
00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:17.942
A few days for what. Kaylie?

118
00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.507
To keep our promise.

119
00:07:22.840 --> 00:07:24.585
And kill it.

120
00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:29.427
(DOG BARKING)

121
00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.839
OK. guys. the couch can go there.

122
00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:38.799
And those boxes are kitchen.

123
00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:39.422
Bam! Bam!

124
00:07:39.448 --> 00:07:41.935
Tim. we don't shoot the movers.

125
00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:46.599
And as soon as I get my files organized. you will have them.

126
00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.199
- (PHONE BUZZING)
- Yes. Shoot.

127
00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:49.786
Can I call you back?

128
00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:54.439
Jeff. I am so sorry I didn't return your call.

129
00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:55.705
I've just been slammed.

130
00:07:55.731 --> 00:07:57.959
It's a lot easier when you have a staff.

131
00:07:57.960 --> 00:07:59.614
Kaylie's under arrest.

132
00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:01.719
She's not here. buddy.

133
00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:03.079
- (TOY GUN FIRING)
- Sneak attack!

134
00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:04.959
You are so dead!

135
00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:06.559
Honey?

136
00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:07.816
And this goes?

137
00:08:07.842 --> 00:08:09.879
OK. against the wall.

138
00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:11.639
Watch the molding.

139
00:08:11.640 --> 00:08:13.442
Thank you. OK.

140
00:08:13.468 --> 00:08:15.759
OK. It's fragile.

141
00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:17.239
(KIDS CHATTERING)

142
00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:19.599
- Hey. guys! Take it outside.
- But. Mom...

143
00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:21.519
The alternative is moving boxes.

144
00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:22.879
GIRL: Oh. come on. Come on.

145
00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:24.759
So we'll talk soon. OK.

146
00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:26.919
WOMAN: Thanks. guys. OK.

147
00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:29.439
I'll be right out.

148
00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:31.479
So you expanded the furniture order?

149
00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.559
I don't know if I'm loving this desk here.

150
00:08:34.560 --> 00:08:38.228
Were you gonna tell me or just wait till I saw the Visa bill?

151
00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:40.701
Hold on.

152
00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:47.679
I was hoping to smooth that over with a three-piece vanity set..

153
00:08:47.680 --> 00:08:51.519
..that is supposed to be here...
Is it not here?

154
00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:53.584
(LAUGHING)

155
00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:57.399
I get it. OK. Do your office however you want.

156
00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:59.079
- Thank you.
- Mm-hm.

157
00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:02.279
It's a bit ostentatious. though. don't you think?

158
00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:05.799
I'm confused. because you wanted the antiques.

159
00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:07.719
And I said I was fine with IKEA.

160
00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:10.439
Yeah. I wanted to get a few pieces to upgrade the place.

161
00:09:10.440 --> 00:09:12.119
not turn it into a showroom.

162
00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:15.399
Listen. we got a new home. a new company.

163
00:09:15.400 --> 00:09:18.704
so we get new furniture.
Makes sense.

164
00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:21.599
Same old wife. though. right?

165
00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:24.506
Well. I told you I was fine with IKEA.

166
00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:28.511
- Kidding.
- I'm not IKEA.

167
00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:39.159
(SIGHS) You sure you prefer this?

168
00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:42.703
Our guest room is a lot nicer than this.

169
00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:46.506
Yeah. I think it might be best.

170
00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:48.626
My own space.

171
00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:58.910
You promised me you'd never forget what really happened.

172
00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:01.710
You promised.

173
00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:04.999
I was ten years old.

174
00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.631
Well...

175
00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:09.799
I'm doing it tomorrow night.

176
00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:13.502
And... I could really. really use your help.

177
00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:21.830
Good night. Tim.

178
00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:52.461
I feel like my scar is more noticeable now than it was ten years ago.

179
00:10:53.560 --> 00:10:54.586
Let me take a look.

180
00:10:54.612 --> 00:10:55.719
I'm a professional.

181
00:10:55.720 --> 00:10:57.239
(GASPS)

182
00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:00.439
(KISSING) What scar?

183
00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:01.391
(CHUCKLING)

184
00:11:01.417 --> 00:11:03.639
We're nowhere near done.

185
00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:04.919
So?

186
00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:07.302
You've only put together the bed.

187
00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.984
That wasn't easy.

188
00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:24.023
(KISSING CONTINUES)

189
00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:32.944
(SIGHS)

190
00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:46.959
(FOOT BANGING)

191
00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:48.864
(GRUNTING)

192
00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:53.110
Damn it.

193
00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:16.984
Shit.

194
00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:41.509
(DOG BARKING)

195
00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:58.031
(GASPS. CHOKING)

196
00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:00.999
No! No! No!

197
00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.599
(SCREAMING) No! No! No!

198
00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:08.212
It's OK.
 It's OK. It's OK.

199
00:14:08.238 --> 00:14:09.719
(SOBBING)

200
00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:10.531
- (PANTING)

201
00:14:10.557 --> 00:14:12.079
- It's OK. It's OK.

202
00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:15.258
It's just one of your night terrors.

203
00:14:15.284 --> 00:14:16.759
It's OK. Shh...

204
00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:20.064
- Shh...
- (BREATHING SLOWS)

205
00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:51.999
(KNOCKING)

206
00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.359
- Hey.
- Hey.

207
00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:55.024
So I requisitioned you your own printer.

208
00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:56.439
You don't have to share anymore.

209
00:14:56.440 --> 00:14:59.679
- We'll take you off the network.
- OK.

210
00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:01.999
Because I guess there were some complaints about people

211
00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.519
printing out their sales reports and finding some really...

212
00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:07.519
graphic crime scene photos from. uh...

213
00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:09.629
your computer.

214
00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:19.799
I noticed you put in a transfer order for the Lasser Glass.

215
00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:22.319
- Yeah. as a repair.
- Oh.

216
00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:24.239
I thought Warren said no repairs.

217
00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:26.224
He changed his mind.

218
00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:29.679
Got to be honest. I'm really just waiting for an explanation

219
00:15:29.680 --> 00:15:32.028
for the corpse print-outs.

220
00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:45.439
I know things have been strange at times.

221
00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:47.519
And you know I'm dealing with some dark stuff.

222
00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:50.221
some parental stuff. with Tim out.

223
00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:56.991
I'll never expect you to understand that part of my life.

224
00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:00.399
Just bear with me a day or two more.

225
00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:02.959
Things will get back to normal.

226
00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:04.625
I promise.

227
00:16:12.720 --> 00:16:16.199
I don't usually get transfer orders to third-party repair houses.

228
00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:19.559
Oh. yeah. the buyer wants his guy to look at it before it ships.

229
00:16:19.560 --> 00:16:21.047
But we both know you'd do it better.

230
00:16:21.073 --> 00:16:22.039
No argument there.

231
00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:23.526
I'll take it there myself.

232
00:16:23.552 --> 00:16:25.494
Babysit it every step of the way.

233
00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:30.306
Better get some furni pads if we're going to move her.

234
00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:57.264
Hello again.

235
00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:09.624
You must be hungry.

236
00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:23.547
I hope this still hurts.

237
00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:45.750
(INHALING QUIETLY)

238
00:18:47.880 --> 00:18:49.545
- You're all set.
- (GASPING)

239
00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:51.871
You all right?

240
00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:56.947
I'm great.

241
00:18:59.960 --> 00:19:01.959
The guys will wrap her up for you in a bit.

242
00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:03.705
Thank you. Warren.

243
00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:19.439
I'll see you at home.

244
00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:20.675
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)

245
00:19:20.701 --> 00:19:22.609
- My car is by the loading dock.

246
00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:25.479
- Hello.
- TIM: Hey.

247
00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:27.519
- Got a phone.
- Cool.

248
00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:28.959
You just need to sign the order.

249
00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:31.759
I don't feel good about the way we left it last night.

250
00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:33.559
Can we meet up somewhere and talk?

251
00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:36.039
Of course. Can you come by the house?

252
00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:37.839
Sure. What's your address?

253
00:19:37.840 --> 00:19:40.950
No. The house.

254
00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:20.719
Yes. I have it in front of me.

255
00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:22.990
I don't know. probably half an hour.

256
00:20:23.016 --> 00:20:23.999
Does that work?

257
00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.559
OK.

258
00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:27.430
Speak then.

259
00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:35.860
(INDISTINCT OVERLAPPING WHISPERS)

260
00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:57.266
(RUSTLING)

261
00:21:14.200 --> 00:21:16.039
(TOY GUN FIRING)

262
00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:17.599
Oh. crap.

263
00:21:17.600 --> 00:21:19.679
I'm gonna get you. you little brat!

264
00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:22.460
(FIRING CONTINUES)

265
00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.319
The answer is still no.

266
00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:27.679
Oh. my God. Ally has one and Maddie has one.

267
00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:29.999
I'm the only kid in my class without a phone.

268
00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.839
That is terrible.

269
00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:33.959
Thanks for nothing. Marie.

270
00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:36.039
(LAUGHING) Oh!

271
00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:39.519
I'm going to run out and get one for you right now. daughter.

272
00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:42.479
love of my life. fruit of my loins.

273
00:21:42.480 --> 00:21:44.703
Well. I wish I'd been a pineapple.

274
00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:52.879
Hey kids. do me a favor and don't ever chew your nails like your father.

275
00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:55.239
- It's gross.
- KAYLIE: Hey. Dad?

276
00:21:55.240 --> 00:21:57.159
OK... He's Dad. I'm Marie.

277
00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:00.479
Who was that lady in your office today?

278
00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:04.910
Yeah. Dad. who was that lady in your office today?

279
00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:07.791
What lady?

280
00:22:09.720 --> 00:22:12.387
I don't know. Just some lady.

281
00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:17.666
I don't know.

282
00:22:34.600 --> 00:22:36.231
(DOOR OPENING)

283
00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:44.479
It looks so small.

284
00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:47.119
- Go on. Dog.
- You named your dog. Dog?

285
00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:50.310
No. He doesn't have a name.

286
00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:52.740
Are you OK?

287
00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:56.704
Oh. of course.

288
00:22:58.000 --> 00:22:59.950
You haven't been here since...

289
00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:05.471
Why don't you look around?

290
00:23:58.320 --> 00:24:02.750
(CHAIN RATTLING)

291
00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:15.799
KAYLIE: The house just sat on the market while I was in the foster system.

292
00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:19.079
Released to me when I turned 18.

293
00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:22.509
I was the only homeowner in the freshman dorms when I started school.

294
00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:28.319
I'm thinking we should try and sell it. though.

295
00:24:28.320 --> 00:24:30.224
You know. after.

296
00:24:32.240 --> 00:24:35.191
So will you help me with something before you go?

297
00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:47.679
How the hell did you expect to get this thing in here yourself?

298
00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:49.319
To be honest. I didn't.

299
00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:51.479
I always thought it'd be both of us.

300
00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:53.759
Over here for now.

301
00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:55.186
OK.

302
00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.667
(PANTING)

303
00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:30.599
What's that?

304
00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:32.868
Yacht anchor. Kill switch.

305
00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:36.959
So. uh... (CLEARS THROAT)

306
00:25:36.960 --> 00:25:38.719
I understand if you don't want to stay.

307
00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:42.388
I accept that. but I got to get started.

308
00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:50.782
I'll stay for a little bit.

309
00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:55.425
Excuse me.

310
00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:00.181
(CAMERAS BEEPING)

311
00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:04.164
(EXHALES) Hello.

312
00:26:04.190 --> 00:26:07.039
My name is Kaylie Ann Russell.

313
00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:08.359
I'm 23 years old.

314
00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:10.799
I'm with my brother. Timothy Alan Russell.

315
00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:12.639
Alan. of course. after his father.

316
00:26:12.640 --> 00:26:14.305
He's...

317
00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:17.679
He's 21 years old.

318
00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:20.399
It's 4:15pm on October 13th.

319
00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:23.079
and we are at 2705 Hawthorne Way.

320
00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:27.559
I'll begin by detailing my precautions before I place and uncover the glass.

321
00:26:27.560 --> 00:26:30.279
There are three cameras. each on its own independent power circuit.

322
00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:33.079
so if any anomalies occur. there can be a lucid. objective record.

323
00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:36.119
I have private land lines for today's experiment. along with my cell phone.

324
00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:38.759
And I will now ask my brother for his phone.

325
00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:42.143
so that I can control all electronic devices.

326
00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:49.671
I just got this. you know.

327
00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:52.191
Thanks. Timbo.

328
00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:56.559
This alarm is set to go off every 45 minutes

329
00:26:56.560 --> 00:26:58.799
to remind me to change the tapes in the cameras.

330
00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:01.479
This alarm is set to go off hourly to remind us to eat.

331
00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:04.479
And we're fully stocked on water to prevent dehydration.

332
00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:06.159
Now. as for the house itself...

333
00:27:06.160 --> 00:27:08.719
each room is fitted with its own thermostat.

334
00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:11.319
from which data is collected by software designed to track and record

335
00:27:11.320 --> 00:27:12.959
temperature fluctuations in hospitals.

336
00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:15.759
Any temperature changes greater than five degrees in either direction

337
00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:17.839
will set off an alarm.

338
00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:19.639
A third precaution is also in place.

339
00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:21.919
but I'll get into that in a few more minutes.

340
00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:24.199
So...

341
00:27:24.200 --> 00:27:26.199
The purpose of today's experiment

342
00:27:26.200 --> 00:27:28.639
is to prove that the object behind me. the Lasser Glass.

343
00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:31.999
is home to an observable. predictable supernatural force.

344
00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.559
There's no scientific equivalent for the word "haunted."

345
00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:38.399
so we'll just say this object is responsible for at least 45 deaths

346
00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:40.719
in the four centuries of its recorded existence...

347
00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:42.959
Can I just stop you for a second?

348
00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:45.183
Don't ever turn off a camera.

349
00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:48.266
Sorry.

350
00:27:54.840 --> 00:27:57.319
The origin of the Lasser Glass is unknown.

351
00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:59.439
so I can't provide a complete history.

352
00:27:59.440 --> 00:28:03.439
but the trail starts in London in 1754.

353
00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.719
Philip Lasser. the 17th Earl of Leicester.

354
00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:09.359
acquired the mirror and hung it over his fireplace. and...

355
00:28:09.360 --> 00:28:10.728
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)

356
00:28:10.754 --> 00:28:12.159
- Another precaution.

357
00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:14.319
Hi. sweetie. How are you?

358
00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:18.079
Well. I'm checking in. uh. as requested.

359
00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:18.861
You all right?

360
00:28:18.887 --> 00:28:20.199
Everything's fine.

361
00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:22.919
I know this is silly to ask. but could you try to call on the hour?

362
00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:24.959
It's about seven past.

363
00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:28.959
- Uh... Sure.
- I'll talk to you in 53 minutes.

364
00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:31.759
And I love you.

365
00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:35.279
I'm expecting regular calls from my fiance. Michael Dumont.

366
00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:37.399
I told him I'm nervous to be spending time with my recently

367
00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:39.199
un-incarcerated brother. with instructions...

368
00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.519
- to notify the authorities immediately
- Wow.

369
00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:41.999
if I do not answer the phone.

370
00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.839
- In the room.
- Nothing personal.

371
00:28:44.840 --> 00:28:48.759
So. in 1755. Philip Lasser was found in their grand fireplace.

372
00:28:48.760 --> 00:28:52.719
Burned beyond recognition. While his estate was dismantled

373
00:28:52.720 --> 00:28:54.439
and scattered throughout southern England.

374
00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:56.999
one of the family's stewards claimed to see Philip reflected in the mirror.

375
00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.279
An allegation apparently taken seriously enough to warrant

376
00:28:59.280 --> 00:29:01.319
a Church investigation into the house.

377
00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:03.439
The glass. thereafter known as the Lasser Glass.

378
00:29:03.440 --> 00:29:06.119
is sold in public auction in 1758.

379
00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:09.239
The next known owner is an American rail road tycoon.

380
00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:11.759
named Robert Clancy. 1864.

381
00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:14.239
Clancy apparently weighed over 300 pounds.

382
00:29:14.240 --> 00:29:16.519
In fact. while attending university in Connecticut.

383
00:29:16.520 --> 00:29:18.239
he was known as the South Windham Whale.

384
00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:21.079
He hung the glass in his ballroom in Atlanta.

385
00:29:21.080 --> 00:29:23.599
Later that year. Robert Clancy is photographed

386
00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:25.759
by a local newspaper and. uh...

387
00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:28.199
Well. he's dropped a few pounds.

388
00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:29.979
His obit was printed a few weeks later.

389
00:29:30.005 --> 00:29:31.439
Doesn't list a cause of death.

390
00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:34.199
Unfortunately. he and his estate and the glass

391
00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:37.919
are presumably destroyed in Sherman's march to the ocean in 1865.

392
00:29:37.920 --> 00:29:40.719
And after that. the glass is lost.

393
00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:43.399
Until it resurfaces in turn-of-the-century New England.

394
00:29:43.400 --> 00:29:47.079
The next case of note is Mary O'Connor. 1904.

395
00:29:47.080 --> 00:29:48.799
She hung the mirror in her private bathroom.

396
00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:52.279
Two weeks later. her niece Beatrice finds Mary dead in the bathtub.

397
00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:56.119
Now. the official coroner's report lists the cause of death as. get this...

398
00:29:56.120 --> 00:29:58.319
dehydration.

399
00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:01.839
The woman died of thirst while soaking in a full tub for three days.

400
00:30:01.840 --> 00:30:06.399
The next case of note is Alice Carden in Lake Geneva. Wisconsin. 1943.

401
00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:09.519
Neighbors reported hearing screams and loud bangs from the house.

402
00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:12.559
The police found the children drowned in a locked cistern.

403
00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:14.159
Alice herself was in the nursery.

404
00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:15.879
and both of her legs are completely shattered.

405
00:30:15.880 --> 00:30:19.359
Her left arm is broken in four places. and six of her ribs are crushed.

406
00:30:19.360 --> 00:30:23.039
In her right hand is a large hammer she's been using to break her own bones.

407
00:30:23.040 --> 00:30:25.759
They find her just as she's going to work on her skull.

408
00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:27.999
Her right arm. though. is completely unharmed.

409
00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.959
Because she needed it. To wield the hammer.

410
00:30:31.960 --> 00:30:34.679
Alice later says she believed she was tucking the children into their beds

411
00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:36.119
as she sealed them into the cistern.

412
00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:37.479
She never recovers from her injuries.

413
00:30:37.480 --> 00:30:39.559
And. oh. the family kept several dogs at the farm.

414
00:30:39.560 --> 00:30:42.639
including an Australian shepherd for the children.

