435
00:30:52.360 --> 00:30:54.799
(TIMER BUZZING)

436
00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:56.431
Let's eat.

437
00:31:01.120 --> 00:31:03.180
Who exactly are you talking to?

438
00:31:03.206 --> 00:31:04.335
On those tapes?

439
00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:11.119
All the people who stared. pointed.

440
00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:13.999
The kids at school who always found out.

441
00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.588
I guess I'm talking to everyone who ever called Dad a murderer.

442
00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:20.309
Called you a murderer.

443
00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:24.519
Look. Kaylie. we were just kids.

444
00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:27.319
We made up a scary story so we wouldn't have to accept the fact

445
00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:29.639
that our father was a murderer.
He was.

446
00:31:29.640 --> 00:31:32.102
He was a sick man who tortured and killed our...

447
00:31:40.200 --> 00:31:43.151
You can call me crazy all you like.

448
00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:47.146
But you're not allowed to talk about him that way.

449
00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:53.479
Tobin Capp. 1955. Starved to death in his own bedroom.

450
00:31:53.480 --> 00:31:55.317
The mirror was hung over his dresser.

451
00:31:55.343 --> 00:31:56.559
He had a pet Dalmatian.

452
00:31:56.560 --> 00:31:58.439
1965. California.

453
00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:01.439
The mirror hangs in the lobby of the Hill Trust Bank in San Diego.

454
00:32:01.440 --> 00:32:04.599
A ten-year teller. Marcia Wicker. locks her manager in the bank vault

455
00:32:04.600 --> 00:32:07.319
and then chews through a live power line.

456
00:32:07.320 --> 00:32:09.999
- 1975. Marisol Chavez...
- Kaylie...

457
00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.919
dies in her bedroom of hemorrhaging due to a miscarriage.

458
00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:14.959
In her nightstand. they find every single one of her teeth

459
00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:17.359
in a little plastic bag and a pair of bloody pliers.

460
00:32:17.360 --> 00:32:19.119
- 2002...
- There's a huge difference

461
00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:20.759
between causation and correlation.

462
00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:22.119
I know the difference. thank you.

463
00:32:22.120 --> 00:32:25.039
OK then. In 2001. Mom and Dad bought that new couch.

464
00:32:25.040 --> 00:32:28.359
Same year. Grandpa had a heart attack. Robbie Schultz got hit by a car.

465
00:32:28.360 --> 00:32:30.319
And our cat ran away.

466
00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:32.799
How much of that do you blame on that couch?

467
00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:34.719
Can I get back to this now?

468
00:32:34.720 --> 00:32:37.079
Sure. but let's get to it. Kaylie.

469
00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:39.667
Let's talk about why we're really here.

470
00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:42.226
(WHISPERS) Let's.

471
00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:45.319
2002.

472
00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:48.829
The Lasser Glass adorns the home office of Alan Russell.

473
00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:51.166
Software designer.

474
00:32:51.192 --> 00:32:52.928
Husband to Marie.

475
00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:55.479
Father to Timothy and Kaylie.

476
00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:56.959
Within two weeks of its arrival.

477
00:32:56.960 --> 00:32:58.999
Marie suffers an intense psychological breakdown

478
00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:02.079
and is tortured and murdered in the family home.

479
00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:03.870
By whom?

480
00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:06.589
By her husband.

481
00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:09.159
So say the police reports.

482
00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:13.067
And her husband was shot to death by her own son.

483
00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:16.542
Right in front of her daughter.

484
00:33:19.600 --> 00:33:22.119
I intend to prove that none of the people I've just described

485
00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:24.479
were responsible for their actions.

486
00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:27.599
Alan Russell was not a murderer. He was a victim.

487
00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:29.119
One of many. as it turns out.

488
00:33:29.120 --> 00:33:31.759
Victims of the supernatural force that resides in that mirror.

489
00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:35.507
So why don't we just end it right now and smash the goddamn thing?

490
00:33:37.080 --> 00:33:39.348
You really don't remember. do you?

491
00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:43.079
(BOTH YELLING)

492
00:33:43.080 --> 00:33:45.462
Remember what?

493
00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:49.543
Please. smash it. by all means.

494
00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:55.381
Okay.

495
00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:13.759
You know. I've learned a lot about what happens to people when they can't...

496
00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:16.301
can't process something horrible.

497
00:34:17.960 --> 00:34:21.707
The mind creates all kinds of protections to help them cope.

498
00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:24.919
And once that belief's taken root.

499
00:34:24.920 --> 00:34:29.225
the mind takes random information and forces it to support that narrative.

500
00:34:32.320 --> 00:34:34.879
How many thousands of records did you have to pore through

501
00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.399
to find 12 or 13 that support your case?

502
00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:40.146
Why did you put the stool down?

503
00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:48.239
Because I'm trying to have a conversation with you.

504
00:34:48.240 --> 00:34:51.439
Uh-huh. Only one person I know of was ever documented

505
00:34:51.440 --> 00:34:53.345
trying to break the mirror.

506
00:34:53.371 --> 00:34:55.039
Oliver Jeffries. 1971.

507
00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:56.959
A teacher at Manhattan's Duhame Academy.

508
00:34:56.960 --> 00:34:58.519
where the mirror hung in the central lecture hall.

509
00:34:58.520 --> 00:35:01.159
One morning he reportedly ran at the mirror with a fireplace poker.

510
00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:02.839
..shouting about how it needed to be destroyed...

511
00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:04.060
..but he never struck a blow.

512
00:35:04.086 --> 00:35:05.279
According to the students.

513
00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:06.839
he stood there quietly for almost a minute

514
00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:09.984
before walking out of the hall and into traffic.

515
00:35:11.160 --> 00:35:13.559
It's clearly capable of defending itself. and...

516
00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:14.235
(WHISPERING)

517
00:35:14.261 --> 00:35:16.172
...I think it just disarmed you.

518
00:35:19.200 --> 00:35:21.759
You know why I didn't smash the mirror. Kaylie?

519
00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:26.588
Besides you getting fired or charged with destruction of property?

520
00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:29.423
It isn't mine to break.

521
00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:32.759
No one can break your delusion for you.

522
00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:34.839
You have to do it yourself.

523
00:35:34.840 --> 00:35:37.461
Which leads me to my final precaution.

524
00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:40.999
You're looking at a 20-pound Danforth anchor.

525
00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:44.279
Another 20 pounds added with barbells. attached to a modified ballast rail

526
00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:46.879
and a spring pin lock connected to a mechanical kitchen timer.

527
00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:50.239
No electricity. which is important. and we're about ten seconds away.

528
00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:52.559
If the timer is not manually reset every 30 minutes.

529
00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:55.159
that is. if no one is here to stop it...

530
00:35:55.160 --> 00:35:56.839
(TIMER TICKING)

531
00:35:56.840 --> 00:36:00.119
(LOUD CLICK)

532
00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:01.631
The mirror goes right there.

533
00:36:01.657 --> 00:36:03.519
And the only thing to prevent that..

534
00:36:03.520 --> 00:36:06.799
..from happening again is our continued survival.

535
00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:09.319
You know why we don't have to wait for it to come out and play?

536
00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:12.279
Because we've got a loaded gun to its head.

537
00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:15.390
And I expect it'll be eager to defend itself.

538
00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:28.469
(TIMER TICKING)

539
00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:50.462
(SIGHS)

540
00:37:40.880 --> 00:37:42.306
Aah!

541
00:37:45.120 --> 00:37:47.309
(INDISTINCT WHISPERING)

542
00:37:56.160 --> 00:37:57.936
FEMALE VOICE: (WHISPERING) It doesn't hurt.

543
00:37:57.962 --> 00:37:58.679
It doesn't hurt.

544
00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:01.984
It doesn't hurt. It doesn't hurt.

545
00:38:26.840 --> 00:38:28.679
(MUSIC PLAYING ON TV)

546
00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:30.349
- (FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

547
00:38:30.375 --> 00:38:31.815
- ALAN: Hey guys?

548
00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:35.741
Come into my office for a second.

549
00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:42.039
I thought I was pretty clear about you guys not messing around in here.

550
00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:43.626
We don't.

551
00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:46.224
I don't like it in here.

552
00:38:46.920 --> 00:38:49.700
All right. well. what is this?

553
00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:55.145
We didn't do that.

554
00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:57.759
OK.

555
00:38:57.760 --> 00:39:02.599
You know. I can hear you guys at night. messing around in here.

556
00:39:02.600 --> 00:39:04.677
I was a kid once. too. I get it.

557
00:39:04.703 --> 00:39:07.079
I know the move has been difficult.

558
00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:09.279
This isn't gonna happen anymore.

559
00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:11.599
OK?

560
00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:14.319
And if you're messing around with your mother's plants.

561
00:39:14.320 --> 00:39:16.384
you're gonna cut that out. too.

562
00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:23.279
TIM: You know what dead plants are evidence of to me?

563
00:39:23.280 --> 00:39:26.424
Problems with the water supply and maybe a bad tank.

564
00:39:27.600 --> 00:39:30.799
I seem to remember drinking out of a Brita filter.

565
00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:32.999
Oliver Jeffries. dead plants in the classroom.

566
00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.039
Tobin Capp. dead plants in the bedroom.

567
00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:37.639
Garden service at Hill Trust Bank couldn't understand

568
00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:40.799
why they had dead plants all over the place.

569
00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:42.439
Live plant.

570
00:39:42.440 --> 00:39:46.039
(SCOFFS)
Live plants in the living room.

571
00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:49.559
Live plants. plants that have life.

572
00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:50.600
These are your rules. by the way.

573
00:39:50.626 --> 00:39:51.199
Give it time.

574
00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:53.199
It always starts with the low-hanging fruit.

575
00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:55.399
It wasn't just the plants it fed on. though.

576
00:39:55.400 --> 00:39:57.519
There was another variable. too.

577
00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:00.221
Dog! (WHISTLES)

578
00:40:03.320 --> 00:40:05.279
Sorry. Dog.

579
00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:07.423
(TIMER BUZZING)

580
00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:13.785
Hydrate.

581
00:40:19.840 --> 00:40:22.984
(DOG WHIMPERING)

582
00:40:24.040 --> 00:40:24.808
Come on. boy.

583
00:40:24.834 --> 00:40:26.639
Come on. Mason. Go fetch.

584
00:40:26.640 --> 00:40:28.999
- Come on. Mason.
- Go fetch.

585
00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.679
Chase the stick. Chase the stick.

586
00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:33.584
Come on. Go. Go.

587
00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:35.439
(SIGHS)

588
00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:37.319
I mean. the whole reason I got this thing

589
00:40:37.320 --> 00:40:39.679
was because you were freaked out that we weren't safe.

590
00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:41.319
Said you saw somebody down here.

591
00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:43.599
Yeah. but that doesn't make me feel safer.

592
00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:46.679
- Quite the opposite. actually.
- (ALAN SIGHS)

593
00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:50.359
OK. I will lock it up. unloaded.

594
00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:54.551
where I'm sure it'll come in very handy in the case of an emergency.

595
00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:00.068
Grotesque cow.

596
00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:09.622
What did you just say to me?

597
00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:12.704
I didn't say anything.

598
00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:22.742
(INDISTINCT VOICES WHISPERING)

599
00:41:27.400 --> 00:41:32.501
(MASON BARKING)

600
00:41:46.800 --> 00:41:50.229
- (GROWLS)
- Ow! Jesus!

601
00:41:53.040 --> 00:41:54.479
Alan!

602
00:41:54.480 --> 00:41:56.908
- (RATTLING DOOR)
- ALAN: I'm working!

603
00:42:00.920 --> 00:42:03.999
(INDISTINCT WHISPERING)

604
00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.029
(ALAN MUTTERING)

605
00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:11.909
Who are you talking to?

606
00:42:17.720 --> 00:42:20.182
Were you gonna do something about the damn barking?

607
00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:25.079
There's something wrong with the dog. Alan. He bit me.

608
00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:27.508
Are you OK?

609
00:42:28.280 --> 00:42:30.344
I'm fine.

610
00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:33.239
(SIGHS)

611
00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:36.759
You know. you are just lost in your own world in here.

612
00:42:36.760 --> 00:42:39.479
I'm not lost in my own world! I'm working!

613
00:42:39.480 --> 00:42:40.959
MARIE: I know that.

614
00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:42.256
I've supported that.

615
00:42:42.282 --> 00:42:44.199
This isn't you working hard.

616
00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:47.519
ALAN: When you start your own business. it's all on you.

617
00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:48.697
I know that. Alan!

618
00:42:48.723 --> 00:42:50.291
I have to do this!

619
00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:56.879
ALAN: Guys.
Listen. you got to do me a special favor today.

620
00:42:56.880 --> 00:42:58.879
I have a golf session with a client.

621
00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:02.479
And I'm gonna need you to stay out of my office. OK?

622
00:43:02.480 --> 00:43:04.464
OK. Dad.

623
00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:07.909
All right. I love you guys.

624
00:43:16.120 --> 00:43:19.264
(WHIMPERING. BARKING)

625
00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:25.239
(SIGHS)

626
00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:29.039
Fine. You wanna go in. you're going in.

627
00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:31.661
Go shit on the CEO's carpet.

628
00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:38.667
(MASON WHIMPERING)

629
00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:45.461
Shit.

630
00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:52.759
Why can't we let him out?

631
00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:55.479
Mom says Mason's grounded.

632
00:43:55.480 --> 00:43:57.519
(DOOR OPENS)

633
00:43:57.520 --> 00:44:00.319
Hey. squirts. Why are you. uh...?

634
00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:02.359
We have got to do something about that damn dog.

635
00:44:02.360 --> 00:44:04.759
(SIGHS) A hello would be nice.

636
00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:06.263
He was a wrecking ball all day.

637
00:44:06.289 --> 00:44:07.959
I had to lock him in your office.

638
00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:10.581
Well. tether him up.

639
00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:29.300
Where is he?

640
00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:32.651
Well. there's the problem.

641
00:44:32.677 --> 00:44:33.679
You're remembering it wrong.

642
00:44:33.680 --> 00:44:35.839
I promise.
I'm not remembering it wrong.

643
00:44:35.840 --> 00:44:36.673
You are. though. Mason...

644
00:44:36.699 --> 00:44:38.039
Alice Carden's Australian shepherd.

645
00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:41.119
Tobin Capp's Dalmatian. the pets were never found. None of them.

646
00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:43.239
Do you remember Mason toward the end?

647
00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:46.599
Vomiting. accidents all over the house.

648
00:44:46.600 --> 00:44:48.879
My therapist had me research Parvo virus.

649
00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:49.320
Oh. my God.

650
00:44:49.346 --> 00:44:50.679
It's a fatal canine illness.

651
00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:53.599
flagged by nausea. aggression. infected urine and stool.

652
00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:56.239
which. incidentally. can kill plants.

653
00:44:56.240 --> 00:44:57.519
Mason was sick.

654
00:44:57.520 --> 00:44:58.999
(RAPID PANTING)

655
00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.199
All right. I'll take him to the vet tomorrow.

656
00:45:01.200 --> 00:45:01.936
ALAN: Bad news.

657
00:45:01.962 --> 00:45:03.799
I don't think we're both coming home.

658
00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:05.750
Mom. where's Mason?

659
00:45:07.880 --> 00:45:09.359
Uh. he's grounded.

660
00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:11.599
Are you saying you remember it happening that way?

661
00:45:11.600 --> 00:45:13.999
- Are you really saying that?
- Why not?

662
00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:14.678
You're wrong.

663
00:45:14.704 --> 00:45:16.399
I saw Mom lock him in the office

664
00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:19.239
and I sat outside that door all day. and nobody went in or out.

665
00:45:19.240 --> 00:45:22.759
Have you ever heard of the fuzzy trace theory of human psychology?

666
00:45:22.760 --> 00:45:24.319
No. But I'm gonna guess you have.

667
00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:26.599
I'm the star of a psychiatric article about it.

668
00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:30.319
Our brains actually encode information as fuzzy traces.

669
00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:32.719
More like a general meaning than an exact record.

670
00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:33.585
This is horseshit. Tim.

671
00:45:33.611 --> 00:45:34.639
Adults are more likely

672
00:45:34.640 --> 00:45:36.719
to combine those traces into false memories.

673
00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:39.319
You saw Mom put the dog in the office on a number of occasions.

674
00:45:39.320 --> 00:45:40.919
My God. what did they do to you?

675
00:45:40.920 --> 00:45:43.399
Way before Dad forbade anyone else from going in the office.

676
00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:45.599
Those traces fused with your memory of that day.

677
00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:47.212
I feel sorry for you.

678
00:45:47.238 --> 00:45:49.439
OK. what's more likely?

679
00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:51.679
That you're misremembering events from 11 years ago.

680
00:45:51.680 --> 00:45:54.028
or that the mirror eats dogs?

681
00:45:56.840 --> 00:45:59.188
Oh. look! It's Dog!

682
00:46:00.160 --> 00:46:02.799
Give it some time.

683
00:46:02.800 --> 00:46:05.519
(SWITCHING VIDEO TAPES)

684
00:46:05.520 --> 00:46:07.106
A little time.

685
00:46:10.840 --> 00:46:13.116
ALAN: There's nothing going on here. woman!

686
00:46:13.142 --> 00:46:14.439
You're really losing it!

687
00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:18.639
MARIE: I can hear you talking to someone. and it sounds like a woman.

688
00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:20.267
ALAN: You know what. you're crazy!

689
00:46:20.293 --> 00:46:21.559
MARIE: I'm not crazy!

690
00:46:21.560 --> 00:46:23.439
I can hear you talking to someone.

691
00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:24.874
ALAN: I mean. listen to yourself!

692
00:46:24.900 --> 00:46:26.439
"I can hear you through the door."

693
00:46:26.440 --> 00:46:28.673
MARIE: Why would I make this up?

694
00:46:28.699 --> 00:46:29.719
I'm not crazy!

695
00:46:29.720 --> 00:46:31.819
ALAN: The water supply is poisoned?

696
00:46:31.845 --> 00:46:33.199
And we got a burglar?

697
00:46:33.200 --> 00:46:35.309
You're losing your mind.

698
00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:47.079
I'm sorry that we woke you up.

699
00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:51.783
Are you and Daddy fighting because of the woman in the office?

700
00:46:54.720 --> 00:46:56.605
You got to remember that woman.

701
00:46:56.631 --> 00:46:57.639
You saw her too.

702
00:46:57.640 --> 00:47:00.519
I convinced myself I saw a lot of things.

703
00:47:00.520 --> 00:47:02.599
But what did we really see?

704
00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:04.639
Mom yelling at Dad in the middle of the night.

705
00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:07.239
Mom said she heard voices. but it was probably just Dad on the phone.

706
00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:09.429
(TIMER BUZZING)

707
00:47:10.800 --> 00:47:12.839
Doesn't explain the woman I saw through the window.

708
00:47:12.840 --> 00:47:14.919
But when did you see her?

709
00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:15.683
The first time?

710
00:47:15.709 --> 00:47:17.159
We were playing in the yard.

711
00:47:17.160 --> 00:47:18.700
Was Mom at home?

712
00:47:19.760 --> 00:47:21.391
Mom was always home.

713
00:47:22.160 --> 00:47:24.301
Are you sure about that?

714
00:47:24.327 --> 00:47:25.932
Because I'm not.

715
00:47:32.160 --> 00:47:33.679
- Oh. shit.
- Shit.

716
00:47:33.680 --> 00:47:35.186
Get back. Get back.

717
00:47:36.160 --> 00:47:39.239
(TYPING)

718
00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:41.159
He was having an affair.
saint that he was.

719
00:47:41.160 --> 00:47:42.040
It was a bad marriage.

720
00:47:42.066 --> 00:47:42.959
Look how it ended up.

721
00:47:42.960 --> 00:47:45.239
- No.
- Our father was a cheater.

722
00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:46.839
- and it drove our mother crazy.
- Stop it.

723
00:47:46.840 --> 00:47:47.756
He snapped and he killed her.

724
00:47:47.782 --> 00:47:48.799
He was gonna do the same to us.

725
00:47:48.800 --> 00:47:50.839
Oh. yeah. A bad marriage.

726
00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:53.279
That explains how Mom had no teeth. no hair. no mind left.

727
00:47:53.280 --> 00:47:54.711
by the time she died.

728
00:47:54.737 --> 00:47:56.279
Yeah. a bad marriage.

729
00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:59.159
That explains those other people we both saw in the house that last night.

730
00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:00.491
He was withdrawn. secretive.

731
00:48:00.517 --> 00:48:01.679
All signs of an affair.

732
00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:03.839
I had access to all of Mom and Dad's stuff.

733
00:48:03.840 --> 00:48:05.719
While you were getting brainwashed. I looked.

734
00:48:05.720 --> 00:48:07.959
Not one credit card receipt. phone call. flower order.

735
00:48:07.960 --> 00:48:09.279
Nothing to suggest an affair.

736
00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:11.079
He was smart enough not to leave a trail.

737
00:48:11.080 --> 00:48:12.399
- (DOG BARKING)
- Quiet!

738
00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:14.159
I talked to his friends and co-workers.

739
00:48:14.160 --> 00:48:15.559
If there was another woman. she was a ghost.

740
00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:18.079
Yeah. I agree. he was withdrawn. secretive. suspicious. sure.

741
00:48:18.080 --> 00:48:19.681
All signs of an affair. fine.

742
00:48:19.707 --> 00:48:21.559
I'm not saying he wasn't seduced.

743
00:48:21.560 --> 00:48:24.022
It's a matter of what seduced him.

744
00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:29.079
(DOG WHIMPERING)

745
00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:31.839
And things have been happening in here while we argue. you know.

746
00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:34.239
You know the temperature in here has risen by three degrees?

747
00:48:34.240 --> 00:48:35.033
Three degrees.

748
00:48:35.059 --> 00:48:36.959
Two people in a small space.

749
00:48:36.960 --> 00:48:38.639
lights burning. electrical equipment...

750
00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:39.992
Phone lines are probably down by now.

751
00:48:40.018 --> 00:48:40.759
Why don't you check?

752
00:48:40.760 --> 00:48:43.222
OK. then.
Let's have a look.

753
00:48:43.800 --> 00:48:45.147
Dial tone.

754
00:48:45.760 --> 00:48:47.079
Static?

755
00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:50.999
Look. Kaylie.
You can deal with this. I did it.

756
00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:52.400
You want to redeem the family name?

757
00:48:52.426 --> 00:48:54.079
You don't need to do it for Mom and Dad.

758
00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:56.519
You only need to do it for yourself.

759
00:48:56.520 --> 00:48:58.679
Oh...

760
00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:02.399
They did a bang-up job on you in there. didn't they?

761
00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:05.879
You were perfectly normal when they locked you up.

762
00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:07.879
You had to go bat-shit to get out.

763
00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:10.559
(DOG WHIMPERING. BARKING)

764
00:49:10.560 --> 00:49:12.319
Mason. stop your goddamn whining!

765
00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:12.896
You know what?

766
00:49:12.922 --> 00:49:13.759
That's it. I'm done.

767
00:49:13.760 --> 00:49:15.119
I know I'm supposed to wait around for you

768
00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:16.519
to find your own way out of this.

769
00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:18.199
But I'm not gonna stand here and let you torture a dog.

770
00:49:18.200 --> 00:49:19.167
What do you think you're doing?

771
00:49:19.193 --> 00:49:19.759
Listen to it!

